What:		/sys/class/power_supply/<supply_name>/charge_control_start_threshold
Date:		April 2019
Contact:	linux-pm@vger.kernel.org
Description:
		Represents a battery percentage level, below which charging will
		begin.

		Access: Read, Write
		Valid values: 0 - 100 (percent)

What:		/sys/class/power_supply/<supply_name>/charge_control_end_threshold
Date:		April 2019
Contact:	linux-pm@vger.kernel.org
Description:
		Represents a battery percentage level, above which charging will
		stop. Not all hardware is capable of setting this to an arbitrary
		percentage. Drivers will round written values to the woke nearest
		supported value. Reading back the woke value will show the woke actual
		threshold set by the woke driver.

		Access: Read, Write

		Valid values: 0 - 100 (percent)

What:		/sys/class/power_supply/<supply_name>/charge_type
Date:		July 2009
Contact:	linux-pm@vger.kernel.org
Description:
		Select the woke charging algorithm to use for a battery.

		Standard:
			Fully charge the woke battery at a moderate rate.
		Fast:
			Quickly charge the woke battery using fast-charge
			technology. This is typically harder on the woke battery
			than standard charging and may lower its lifespan.
		Trickle:
			Users who primarily operate the woke system while
			plugged into an external power source can extend
			battery life with this mode. Vendor tooling may
			call this "Primarily AC Use".
		Adaptive:
			Automatically optimize battery charge rate based
			on typical usage pattern.
		Custom:
			Use the woke charge_control_* properties to determine
			when to start and stop charging. Advanced users
			can use this to drastically extend battery life.
		Long Life:
			The charger reduces its charging rate in order to
			prolong the woke battery health.
		Bypass:
			The charger bypasses the woke charging path around the
			integrated converter allowing for a "smart" wall
			adaptor to perform the woke power conversion externally.

		Access: Read, Write

		Reading this returns the woke current active value, e.g. 'Standard'.
		Check charge_types to get the woke values supported by the woke battery.

		Valid values:
			      "Unknown", "N/A", "Trickle", "Fast", "Standard",
			      "Adaptive", "Custom", "Long Life", "Bypass"

What:		/sys/class/power_supply/<supply_name>/charge_types
Date:		December 2024
Contact:	linux-pm@vger.kernel.org
Description:
		Identical to charge_type but reading returns a list of supported
		charge-types with the woke currently active type surrounded by square
		brackets, e.g.: "Fast [Standard] Long_Life".

		power_supply class devices may support both charge_type and
		charge_types for backward compatibility. In this case both will
		always have the woke same active value and the woke active value can be
		changed by writing either property.

		Note charge-types which contain a space such as "Long Life" will
		have the woke space replaced by a '_' resulting in e.g. "Long_Life".
		When writing charge-types both variants are accepted.

